# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: knex-querybuilder
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] A **data access layer** (**DAL**) is a software architectural layer that provides access to data from one or more sources, such as a relational database, NoSQL database, SQL query engine, file system, or other persistent storage.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] It separates client code from the details of storage systems, query execution, connection handling, and data retrieval.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] Data access layers are commonly used to centralize data access logic, reduce coupling between applications and data sources, and provide a consistent interface for retrieving, writing, or querying data.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] Depending on the system, a data access layer may be implemented as application code, a shared library, an intermediary service, or part of a broader database abstraction layer.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] In application software, a data access layer provides a boundary between business logic or application code and the systems used to store or retrieve data.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] For example, a data access layer may expose methods or interfaces for retrieving, writing, or querying data while hiding details such as connection management, SQL statements, storage APIs, error handling, and result conversion.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] Depending on the application, the layer may return objects, records, tabular results, documents, streams, or other representations of data.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] A common implementation is a set of classes, functions, or methods that directly reference database queries, stored procedures, storage APIs, or other data sources.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] For example, instead of using commands such as *insert*, *delete*, and *update* throughout an application to access a specific table, methods such as *registerUser* or *loginUser* may be implemented inside the data access layer.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] Business logic methods from an application can also be mapped to the data access layer.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] Instead of making several database queries directly, an application can call a single DAL method that abstracts those database calls.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] Applications using a data access layer may be either dependent on or independent from a particular database server.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] If the data access layer supports multiple database systems, the application can use any database system that the DAL can access.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] In either case, the data access layer provides a centralized location for calls into the underlying data store, which can make it easier to maintain, test, or port the application to other storage systems.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] A data access layer can be implemented using several patterns and technologies, including data access objects, repositories, stored procedures, query builders, database drivers, or object–relational mapping tools.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] These mechanisms may implement part or all of a data access layer, but are not always equivalent to the layer itself.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] Object–relational mapping tools are commonly used in data access layers for object-oriented applications that map records in a relational database to objects in a programming language.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] Other data access layers may expose lower-level database interfaces, tabular results, document-oriented data, files, streams, or protocol-level interfaces.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] A data access layer may be used to abstract differences between multiple underlying data systems, allowing applications to access them through a more consistent interface.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] In such designs, applications call the DAL rather than interacting directly with each database or storage system.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] The layer may then handle connection management, query generation, result mapping, error handling, and other implementation details.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] A data access layer may be implemented as a shared library or as an intermediary service, such as a proxy or gateway.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] In this configuration, client applications or services connect to the data access layer, which then communicates with one or more underlying databases or query engines.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] This can provide a common location for authentication, authorization, logging, routing, and translation between different database interfaces.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] Data access layers may expose or use standardized interfaces and protocols for database access.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] Examples include Open Database Connectivity (ODBC), Java Database Connectivity (JDBC), database-native wire protocols, and newer interfaces such as Apache Arrow Database Connectivity (ADBC) and Arrow Flight SQL.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] In systems that support multiple data stores, a data access layer may provide a consistent interface while using different drivers, protocols, or query mechanisms internally.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] A data access layer is related to, but broader than, a data access object, which is usually an object-oriented design pattern for encapsulating access to a persistence mechanism.
[src:knex-querybuilder/data-access-layer] It is also related to a database abstraction layer, which focuses on hiding differences between database systems.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The **`Promise`** object represents the eventual completion (or failure) of an asynchronous operation and its resulting value.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] To learn about the way promises work and how you can use them, we advise you to read Using promises first.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] A `Promise` is a proxy for a value not necessarily known when the promise is created.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] It allows you to associate handlers with an asynchronous action's eventual success value or failure reason.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] This lets asynchronous methods return values like synchronous methods: instead of immediately returning the final value, the asynchronous method returns a *promise* to supply the value at some point in the future.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The *eventual state* of a pending promise can either be *fulfilled* with a value or *rejected* with a reason (error).
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] When either of these options occur, the associated handlers queued up by a promise's `then` method are called.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] If the promise has already been fulfilled or rejected when a corresponding handler is attached, the handler will be called, so there is no race condition between an asynchronous operation completing and its handlers being attached.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] A promise is said to be *settled* if it is either fulfilled or rejected, but not pending.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] (Flowchart showing how the Promise state transitions between pending, fulfilled, and rejected via then/catch handlers.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] A pending promise can become either fulfilled or rejected.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] If fulfilled, the "on fulfillment" handler, or first parameter of the then() method, is executed and carries out further asynchronous actions.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] You will also hear the term *resolved* used with promises — this means that the promise is settled or "locked-in" to match the eventual state of another promise, and further resolving or rejecting it has no effect.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The States and fates document from the original Promise proposal contains more details about promise terminology.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Colloquially, "resolved" promises are often equivalent to "fulfilled" promises, but as illustrated in "States and fates", resolved promises can be pending or rejected as well.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] This promise is already *resolved* at the time when it's created (because the `resolveOuter` is called synchronously), but it is resolved with another promise, and therefore won't be *fulfilled* until 1 second later, when the inner promise fulfills.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] In practice, the "resolution" is often done behind the scenes and not observable, and only its fulfillment or rejection are.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] `Promise` itself has no first-class protocol for cancellation, but you may be able to directly cancel the underlying asynchronous operation, typically using `AbortController`.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The promise methods `then()`, `catch()`, and `finally()` are used to associate further action with a promise that becomes settled.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The `then()` method takes up to two arguments; the first argument is a callback function for the fulfilled case of the promise, and the second argument is a callback function for the rejected case.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The `catch()` and `finally()` methods call `then()` internally and make error handling less verbose.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] For example, a `catch()` is really just a `then()` without passing the fulfillment handler.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] As these methods return promises, they can be chained.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] We will use the following terminology: *initial promise* is the promise on which `then` is called; *new promise* is the promise returned by `then`.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The two callbacks passed to `then` are called *fulfillment handler* and *rejection handler*, respectively.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The settled state of the initial promise determines which handler to execute.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The completion of the handler determines the settled state of the new promise.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] For example, in the code above, if `myPromise` rejects, `handleRejectedA` will be called, and if `handleRejectedA` completes normally (without throwing or returning a rejected promise), the promise returned by the first `then` will be fulfilled instead of staying rejected.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Therefore, if an error must be handled immediately, but we want to maintain the error state down the chain, we must throw an error of some type in the rejection handler.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] On the other hand, in the absence of an immediate need, we can leave out error handling until the final `catch()` handler.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Each time, JavaScript picks a job from the queue and executes it to completion.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The jobs are defined by the executor of the `Promise()` constructor, the handlers passed to `then`, or any platform API that returns a promise.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The promises in a chain represent the dependency relationship between these jobs.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] When a promise settles, the respective handlers associated with it are added to the back of the job queue.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] A promise can participate in more than one chain.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] For the following code, the fulfillment of `promiseA` will cause both `handleFulfilled1` and `handleFulfilled2` to be added to the job queue.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Because `handleFulfilled1` is registered first, it will be invoked first.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] An action can be assigned to an already settled promise.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] In this case, the action is added immediately to the back of the job queue and will be performed when all existing jobs are completed.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Therefore, an action for an already "settled" promise will occur only after the current synchronous code completes and at least one loop-tick has passed.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] This guarantees that promise actions are asynchronous.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The JavaScript ecosystem had made multiple Promise implementations long before it became part of the language.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Despite being represented differently internally, at the minimum, all Promise-like objects implement the *Thenable* interface.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] A thenable implements the `.then()` method, which is called with two callbacks: one for when the promise is fulfilled, one for when it's rejected.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] To interoperate with the existing Promise implementations, the language allows using thenables in place of promises.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] For example, `Promise.resolve` will not only resolve promises, but also trace thenables.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The `then()` method is responsible for scheduling the execution of the provided `onFulfilled` and `onRejected` callbacks.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Its semantics, including error handling and asynchronicity, are precisely defined in the Promises/A+ specification, and we shall not repeat them here.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] It's very rare that you need to implement a thenable yourself; even if you are not using native promises, you would probably be using a Promise library such as Bluebird.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Fulfills when **all** of the promises fulfill; rejects when **any** of the promises rejects.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Fulfills when **any** of the promises fulfills; rejects when **all** of the promises reject.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Settles when **any** of the promises settles.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] In other words, fulfills when any of the promises fulfills; rejects when any of the promises rejects.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] All these methods take an iterable of promises (thenables, to be exact) and return a new promise.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] They all support subclassing, which means they can be called on subclasses of `Promise`, and the result will be a promise of the subclass type.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] To do so, the subclass's constructor must implement the same signature as the `Promise()` constructor — accepting a single `executor` function that can be called with the `resolve` and `reject` callbacks as parameters.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The subclass must also have a `resolve` static method that can be called like `Promise.resolve()` to resolve values to promises.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Note that JavaScript is single-threaded by nature, so at a given instant, only one task will be executing, although control can shift between different promises, making execution of the promises appear concurrent.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Parallel execution in JavaScript can only be achieved through worker threads.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The constructor is primarily used to wrap functions that do not already support promises.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Returns the constructor used to construct return values from promise methods.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Takes an iterable of promises as input and returns a single `Promise`.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] This returned promise fulfills when all of the input's promises fulfill (including when an empty iterable is passed), with an array of the fulfillment values.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] It rejects when any of the input's promises reject, with this first rejection reason.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] This returned promise fulfills when all of the input's promises settle (including when an empty iterable is passed), with an array of objects that describe the outcome of each promise.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] This returned promise fulfills when any of the input's promises fulfill, with this first fulfillment value.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] It rejects when all of the input's promises reject (including when an empty iterable is passed), with an `AggregateError` containing an array of rejection reasons.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] This returned promise settles with the eventual state of the first promise that settles.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Returns a new `Promise` object that is rejected with the given reason.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Returns a `Promise` object that is resolved with the given value.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] If the value is a thenable (i.e., has a `then` method), the returned promise will "follow" that thenable, adopting its eventual state; otherwise, the returned promise will be fulfilled with the value.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Takes a callback of any kind (returns or throws, synchronously or asynchronously) and wraps its result in a `Promise`.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Returns an object containing a new `Promise` object and two functions to resolve or reject it, corresponding to the two parameters passed to the executor of the `Promise()` constructor.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] These properties are defined on `Promise.prototype` and shared by all `Promise` instances.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The constructor function that created the instance object.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] For `Promise` instances, the initial value is the `Promise` constructor.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The initial value of the `[Symbol.toStringTag]` property is the string `"Promise"`.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] This property is used in `Object.prototype.toString()`.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Appends a rejection handler callback to the promise, and returns a new promise resolving to the return value of the callback if it is called, or to its original fulfillment value if the promise is instead fulfilled.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Appends a handler to the promise, and returns a new promise that is resolved when the original promise is resolved.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The handler is called when the promise is settled, whether fulfilled or rejected.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Appends fulfillment and rejection handlers to the promise, and returns a new promise resolving to the return value of the called handler, or to its original settled value if the promise was not handled (i.e., if the relevant handler `onFulfilled` or `onRejected` is not a function).
