[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] To understand this, start by scrolling to the bottom of the code block, and examine the promise chain.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Upon provision of an initial promise, a chain of promises can follow.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The chain is composed of `.then()` calls, and typically (but not necessarily) has a single `.catch()` at the end, optionally followed by `.finally()`.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] In this example, the promise chain is initiated by a custom-written `new Promise()` construct; but in actual practice, promise chains more typically start with an API function (written by someone else) that returns a promise.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The example function `tetheredGetNumber()` shows that a promise generator will utilize `reject()` while setting up an asynchronous call, or within the call-back, or both.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The function `promiseGetWord()` illustrates how an API function might generate and return a promise in a self-contained manner.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Note that the function `troubleWithGetNumber()` ends with a `throw`.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] That is forced because a promise chain goes through all the `.then()` promises, even after an error, and without the `throw`, the error would seem "fixed".
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] This is a hassle, and for this reason, it is common to omit `onRejected` throughout the chain of `.then()` promises, and just have a single `onRejected` in the final `catch()`.
