[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] A settings object is an environment that provides additional information when JavaScript code is running.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] This includes the realm and module map, as well as HTML specific information such as the origin.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] The incumbent settings object is tracked in order to ensure that the browser knows which one to use for a given piece of user code.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] To better picture this, we can take a closer look at how the realm might be an issue.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] A **realm** can be roughly thought of as the global object.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] What is unique about realms is that they hold all of the necessary information to run JavaScript code.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] This includes objects like `Array` and `Error`.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] Each settings object has its own "copy" of these and they are not shared.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] That can cause some unexpected behavior in relation to promises.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] In order to get around this, we track something called the **incumbent settings object**.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] This represents information specific to the context of the user code responsible for a certain function call.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] To illustrate this a bit further we can take a look at how an `<iframe>` embedded in a document communicates with its host.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] In the above example, the inner text of the `<iframe>` will be updated only if the incumbent settings object is tracked.
[src:knex-querybuilder/global-objects-promise] This is because without tracking the incumbent, we may end up using the wrong environment to send the message.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Knex can be used as an SQL query builder in both Node.JS and the browser, limited to WebSQL's constraints (like the inability to drop tables or read schemas).
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Composing SQL queries in the browser for execution on the server is highly discouraged, as this can be the cause of serious security vulnerabilities.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] The browser builds outside of WebSQL are primarily for learning purposes - for example, you can pop open the console and build queries on this page using the **knex** object.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Knex can be built using a JavaScript build tool such as browserify or webpack.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] In fact, this documentation uses a webpack build which includes knex.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] View source on this page to see the browser build in-action (the global `knex` variable).
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] The `knex` module is itself a function which takes a configuration object for Knex, accepting a few parameters.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] The `client` parameter is required and determines which client adapter will be used with the library.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Knex's PostgreSQL client allows you to set the initial search path for each connection automatically using an additional option "searchPath" as shown below.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] When using the PostgreSQL driver, another usage pattern for instantiating the Knex configuration object could be to use a `connection: {}` object details to specify various flags such as enabling SSL, a connection string, and individual connection configuration fields all in the same object.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] If `connectionString` is highest priority to use.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] If left unspecified then connection details will be determined using the individual connection fields (`host`, `port`, etc), and finally an SSL configuration will be enabled based on a truthy value of `config["DB_SSL"]` which will also accept self-signed certificates.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] When you use the SQLite3 or Better-SQLite3 adapter, there is a filename required, not a network connection.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] You can also run either SQLite3 or Better-SQLite3 with an in-memory database by providing `:memory:` as the filename.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] When you use the SQLite3 adapter, you can set flags used to open the connection.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] With the Better-SQLite3 adapter, you can use `options.nativeBinding` to specify the location of the adapter's compiled C++ addon.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] This can be useful when your build system does a lot of transformation/relocation of files.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] For handling large integers (larger than `Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER`), you can use `connection.options.safeIntegers` to enable BigInt support.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] For more information, see the Better-SQLite3 documentation on database connection options.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] When you use the MSSQL client, you can define a `mapBinding` function to define your own logic for mapping from knex query parameters to `tedious` types.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Returning undefined from the function will fallback to the default mapping.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] The database version can be added in knex configuration, when you use the PostgreSQL adapter to connect a non-standard database.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] A function can be used to determine the connection configuration dynamically.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] This function receives no parameters, and returns either a configuration object or a promise for a configuration object.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] By default, the configuration object received via a function is cached and reused for all connections.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] To change this behavior, an `expirationChecker` function can be returned as part of the configuration object.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] The `expirationChecker` is consulted both when creating a new connection and before reusing an existing one from the pool.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] If it returns `true`, Knex refreshes the connection settings from your provider and discards the old connection so the pool can create a new one with the updated configuration.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] You can also connect via a unix domain socket, which will ignore host and port.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Initializing the library should normally only ever happen once in your application, as it creates a connection pool for the current database, you should use the instance returned from the initialize call throughout your library.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Specify the client for the particular flavour of SQL you are interested in.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] The `connectionPool` option is available since knex v3.3.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Instead of providing a `connection` config and letting knex create its own pool, you can pass an existing pool instance via `connectionPool`.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] This is mutually exclusive with `connection` — you must use one or the other.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] When `connectionPool` is provided, knex does **not** own the pool lifecycle.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Calling `knex.destroy()` releases the reference but does **not** close the pool — you are responsible for calling `pool.end()` (or `pool.close()` for oracledb) yourself.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] `KnexPool` extends tarn's `Pool` and is exported on the knex namespace.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] You can also pass a plain tarn `Pool` instance directly — any object with the tarn pool interface (`acquire`, `release`, `destroy`, `numFree`, `numUsed`, `numPendingAcquires`) is accepted without wrapping.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] When using `connectionPool`, the `pool` config option (min, max, afterCreate, validate, etc.) is ignored since knex is not creating the pool.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Configure these on the pool instance you provide instead.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] The `connectionPool` option is supported for **pg**, **mysql**, **mysql2**, and **oracledb** dialects when passing native driver pools.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] SQLite and MSSQL do not support native driver pools, but you can still pass a tarn `Pool` or `KnexPool` to any dialect.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Passing a `debug: true` flag on your initialization object will turn on debugging for all queries.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Passing an `asyncStackTraces: true` flag on your initialization object will turn on stack trace capture for all query builders, raw queries and schema builders.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] When a DB driver returns an error, this previously captured stack trace is thrown instead of a new one.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] This helps to mitigate default behaviour of `await` in node.js/V8 which blows the stack away.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] This has small performance overhead, so it is advised to use only for development.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] The client created by the configuration initializes a connection pool, using the tarn.js library.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] This connection pool has a default setting of a `min: 2, max: 10` for the MySQL and PG libraries, and a single connection for sqlite3 (due to issues with utilizing multiple connections on a single file).
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] To change the config settings for the pool, pass a `pool` option as one of the keys in the initialize block.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Note that the default value of `min` is 2 only for historical reasons.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] It can result in problems with stale connections, despite tarn's default idle connection timeout of 30 seconds, which is only applied when there are more than `min` active connections.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] It is recommended to set `min: 0` so all idle connections can be terminated.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Checkout the tarn.js library for more information.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] If you ever need to explicitly teardown the connection pool, you may use `knex.destroy([callback])`.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] You may use `knex.destroy` by passing a callback, or by chaining as a promise, just not both.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] To manually initialize a destroyed connection pool, you may use `knex.initialize([config])`, if no config is passed, it will use the first knex configuration used.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] You can provide a `pool.validate` function to decide if a pooled connection should be reused.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] It can be sync or async; return/resolve `false` (or throw) to discard the connection and force the pool to replace it.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] To force periodic churn (e.g., to rebalance traffic to new reader instances), set `maxConnectionLifetimeMillis`.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Optionally add `maxConnectionLifetimeJitterMillis` to spread reconnections out and avoid a thundering herd.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] `afterCreate` callback (rawDriverConnection, done) is called when the pool aquires a new connection from the database server. done(err, connection) callback must be called for `knex` to be able to decide if the connection is ok or if it should be discarded right away from the pool.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] `acquireConnectionTimeout` defaults to 60000ms and is used to determine how long knex should wait before throwing a timeout error when acquiring a connection is not possible.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] The most common cause for this is using up all the pool for transaction connections and then attempting to run queries outside of transactions while the pool is still full.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] The error thrown will provide information on the query the connection was for to simplify the job of locating the culprit.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] The valid types are 'DATE', 'NUMBER' and 'CLOB'.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] When any column having one of the specified types is queried, the column data is returned as a string instead of the default representation.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] The default value of `precision` to use when creating a datetime column with the schema builder.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] When the precision of a timestamp column is unspecified in postgres, it defaults to 6 (microseconds), which is finer-grained than Javascript's `Date` class (milliseconds).
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] This can lead to unexpected behavior when database-generated values (such as default "now" timestamp values) are read into JS and written back to the database.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] As a workaround, timestamp columns can be created with a lower precision that matches the JS runtime.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] For convenience, any migration configuration may be specified when initializing the library.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Read the Migrations section for more information and a full list of configuration options.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Hook for modifying returned rows, before passing them forward to user.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] One can do for example snake_case -> camelCase conversion for returned columns with this hook.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] The `queryContext` is only available if configured for a query builder instance via queryContext.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Knex supports transforming identifier names automatically to quoted versions for each dialect.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] For example `'Table.columnName as foo'` for PostgreSQL is converted to "Table"."columnName" as "foo".
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] With `wrapIdentifier` one may override the way how identifiers are transformed.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] It can be used to override default functionality and for example to help doing `camelCase` -> `snake_case` conversion.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] For example, with the query builder, `knex('table').withSchema('foo').select('table.field as otherName').where('id', 1)` will call `wrapIdentifier` converter for following values `'table'`, `'foo'`, `'table'`, `'field'`, `'otherName'` and `'id'`.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Knex contains some internal log functions for printing warnings, errors, deprecations, and debug information when applicable.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] These log functions typically log to the console, but can be overwritten using the log option and providing alternative functions.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Different log functions can be used for separate knex instances.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Knex builds an error message in case of query error.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] By default Knex adds compiled SQL (`SELECT * FROM users WHERE password = 'myPassword'`) to the error message.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] This can be changed to parameterized SQL (`SELECT * FROM users WHERE password = ?`) by setting `compileSqlOnError` to `false`.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] While knex is written in JavaScript, officially supported TypeScript bindings are available (within the knex npm package).
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] However it is to be noted that TypeScript support is currently best-effort.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Knex has a very flexible API and not all usage patterns can be type-checked and in most such cases we err on the side of flexibility.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] In particular, lack of type errors doesn't currently guarantee that the generated queries will be correct and therefore writing tests for them is recommended even if you are using TypeScript.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] Many of the APIs accept `TRecord` and `TResult` type parameters, using which we can specify the type of a row in the database table and the type of the result of the query respectively.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] This is helpful for auto-completion when using TypeScript-aware editors like VSCode.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] To reduce boilerplate and add inferred types, you can augment `Tables` interface in `'knex/types/tables'` module.
[src:knex-querybuilder/guide] When TypeScript is configured to use a modern module resolution setting (`node16`, `nodenext`, etc.), the compiler expects that the declared module name ends with a `.js` file type.
[src:knex-querybuilder/knex-knex] You can report bugs and discuss features on the GitHub issues page or send tweets to @kibertoad.
[src:knex-querybuilder/knex-knex] For support and questions, join our Gitter channel.
[src:knex-querybuilder/knex-knex] We have several examples on the website.
[src:knex-querybuilder/knex-knex] If you are launching your Node application with `--experimental-modules`, `knex.mjs` should be picked up automatically and named ESM import should work out-of-the-box.
[src:knex-querybuilder/query-language] A **query language**, also known as **data query language** or **database query language** (**DQL**), is a computer language used to make queries in databases and information systems.
[src:knex-querybuilder/query-language] In database systems, query languages rely on strict theory to retrieve information.
[src:knex-querybuilder/query-language] A well known example is the Structured Query Language (SQL).
[src:knex-querybuilder/query-language] Broadly, query languages can be classified according to whether they are *database* query languages or *information retrieval* query languages.
[src:knex-querybuilder/query-language] The difference is that a **database query language** attempts to give factual answers to factual questions, while an **information retrieval query language** attempts to find documents containing information that is relevant to an area of inquiry.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Introduced in the 1970s, SQL offered two main advantages over older read–write APIs such as ISAM or VSAM.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Firstly, it introduced the concept of accessing many records with one single command.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Secondly, it eliminates the need to specify *how* to reach a record, i.e., with or without an index.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Originally based upon relational algebra and tuple relational calculus, SQL consists of many types of statements, which may be informally classed as sublanguages, commonly: data query language (DQL), data definition language (DDL), data control language (DCL), and data manipulation language (DML).
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] The scope of SQL includes data query, data manipulation (insert, update, and delete), data definition (schema creation and modification), and data access control.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Although SQL is essentially a declarative language (4GL), it also includes procedural elements.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] SQL was one of the first commercial languages to use Edgar F.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] The model was described in his influential 1970 paper, "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Despite not entirely adhering to the relational model as described by Codd, SQL became the most widely used database language.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] SQL became a standard of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) in 1986 and of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1987.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Since then, the standard has been revised multiple times to include a larger set of features and incorporate common extensions.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Despite the existence of standards, virtually no implementations in existence adhere to it fully, and most SQL code requires at least some changes before being ported to different database systems.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] SQL was initially developed at IBM by Donald D.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Boyce after learning about the relational model from Edgar F.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] This version, initially called SEQUEL (Structured English Query Language), was designed to manipulate and retrieve data stored in IBM's original quasirelational database management system, System R, which a group at IBM San Jose Research Laboratory had developed during the 1970s.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Chamberlin and Boyce's first attempt at a relational database language was SQUARE (Specifying Queries in A Relational Environment), but it was difficult to use due to subscript/superscript notation.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] After moving to the San Jose Research Laboratory in 1973, they began work on a sequel to SQUARE.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] The original name SEQUEL, which is widely regarded as a pun on QUEL, the query language of Ingres, was later changed to SQL (dropping the vowels) because "SEQUEL" was a trademark of the UK-based Hawker Siddeley Dynamics Engineering Limited company.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] The label SQL later became the acronym for Structured Query Language.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] After testing SQL at customer test sites to determine the usefulness and practicality of the system, IBM began developing commercial products based on their System R prototype, including System/38, SQL/DS, and IBM Db2, which were commercially available in 1979, 1981, and 1983, respectively.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] IBM's endorsement caused the industry to move to SQL from alternatives like QUEL.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] In the late 1970s, Relational Software, Inc.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] (now Oracle Corporation) saw the potential of the concepts described by Codd, Chamberlin, and Boyce, and developed their own SQL-based RDBMS with aspirations of selling it to the U.S.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Navy, Central Intelligence Agency, and other U.S. government agencies.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] In June 1979, Relational Software introduced one of the first commercially available implementations of SQL, Oracle V2 (Version2) for VAX computers.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] By 1986, ANSI and ISO standard groups officially adopted the standard "Database Language SQL" language definition.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] SQL implementations are incompatible between vendors and do not necessarily completely follow standards.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] In particular, date and time syntax, string concatenation, `NULL`s, and comparison case sensitivity vary from vendor to vendor.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] PostgreSQL and Mimer SQL strive for standards compliance, though PostgreSQL does not adhere to the standard in all cases.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] For example, the folding of unquoted names to lower case in PostgreSQL is incompatible with the SQL standard, which says that unquoted names should be folded to upper case.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Thus, according to the standard, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO`, not `foo`.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Popular implementations of SQL commonly omit support for basic features of Standard SQL, such as the `DATE` or `TIME` data types.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] The most obvious such examples, and incidentally the most popular commercial and proprietary SQL DBMSs, are Oracle (whose `DATE` behaves as `DATETIME`, and lacks a `TIME` type) and MS SQL Server (before the 2008 version).
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] As a result, SQL code can rarely be ported between database systems without modifications.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] SQL was adopted as a standard by the ANSI in 1986 as SQL-86 and the ISO in 1987.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] It is maintained by *ISO/IEC JTC 1, Information technology, Subcommittee SC 32, Data management and interchange*.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Until 1996, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) data-management standards program certified SQL DBMS compliance with the SQL standard.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Vendors now self-certify the compliance of their products.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] The original standard declared that the official pronunciation for "SQL" was an initialism: /ˌɛsˌkjuːˈɛl/ ("ess cue el").
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Regardless, many English-speaking database professionals (including Donald Chamberlin himself) use the acronym-like pronunciation of /ˈsiːkwəl/ ("sequel"), mirroring the language's prerelease development name, "SEQUEL".
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] The standard is commonly denoted by the pattern: *ISO/IEC 9075-n:yyyy Part n: title*, or, as a shortcut, *ISO/IEC 9075*.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Interested parties may purchase the standards documents from ISO, IEC, or ANSI.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] SQL is designed for a specific purpose: to query data contained in a relational database.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] SQL is a set-based, declarative programming language, not an imperative programming language like C or BASIC.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] However, extensions to Standard SQL add procedural programming language functionality, such as control-of-flow constructs.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] In addition to the standard SQL/PSM extensions and proprietary SQL extensions, procedural and object-oriented programmability is available on many SQL platforms via DBMS integration with other languages.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] The SQL standard defines SQL/JRT extensions (SQL Routines and Types for the Java Programming Language) to support Java code in SQL databases.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Microsoft SQL Server 2005 uses the SQLCLR (SQL Server Common Language Runtime) to host managed .NET assemblies in the database, while prior versions of SQL Server were restricted to unmanaged extended stored procedures primarily written in C.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] PostgreSQL lets users write functions in a wide variety of languages—including Perl, Python, Tcl, JavaScript (PL/V8) and C.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] A distinction should be made between alternatives to SQL as a language, and alternatives to the relational model itself.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Below are proposed relational alternatives to the SQL language.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] See navigational database and NoSQL for alternatives to the relational model.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM from 1988 to 1994.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] DRDA enables network-connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] An interactive user or program can issue SQL statements to a local RDB and receive tables of data and status indicators in reply from remote RDBs.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] SQL statements can also be compiled and stored in remote RDBs as packages and then invoked by package name.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] This is important for the efficient operation of application programs that issue complex, high-frequency queries.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] It is especially important when the tables to be accessed are located in remote systems.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Distributed SQL processing ala DRDA is distinctive from contemporary distributed SQL databases.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] SQL deviates in several ways from its theoretical foundation, the relational model and its tuple calculus.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] In that model, a table is a set of tuples, while in SQL, tables and query results are lists of rows; the same row may occur multiple times, and the order of rows can be employed in queries (e.g., in the `LIMIT` clause).
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Critics argue that SQL should be replaced with a language that returns strictly to the original foundation: for example, see *The Third Manifesto* by Hugh Darwen and C.J.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Early specifications did not support major features, such as primary keys.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Result sets could not be named, and subqueries had not been defined.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] The lack of sum types has been described as a roadblock to full use of SQL's user-defined types.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] JSON support, for example, needed to be added by a new standard in 2016.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] The concept of Null is the subject of some debate.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] The Null marker indicates the absence of a value, and is distinct from a value of 0 for an integer column or an empty string for a text column.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] The concept of Nulls enforces the 3-valued-logic in SQL, which is a concrete implementation of the general 3-valued logic.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] Another popular criticism is that it allows duplicate rows, making integration with languages such as Python, whose data types might make accurately representing the data difficult, in terms of parsing and by the absence of modularity.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] This is usually avoided by declaring a primary key, or a unique constraint, with one or more columns that uniquely identify a row in the table.
[src:knex-querybuilder/sql] In a sense similar to object–relational impedance mismatch, a mismatch occurs between the declarative SQL language and the procedural languages in which SQL is typically embedded.
